---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Hero from '../components/Hero.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import Email from '../components/Email.astro';
import { SITE } from '../lib/site';

const title = 'About Apriori Studio';
const description =
  'Apriori Studio is a small UK software studio building modern websites and mobile apps end-to-end. Honest pricing, plain English, and a senior team.';
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <Hero image="/heroes/about.webp" tint="amber">
    <span class="kicker text-amber-300">About</span>
    <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-5xl font-semibold tracking-tight leading-[1.05] hero-shadow">
      A small UK studio,<br class="hidden md:block" /> built around the work
    </h1>
    <p class="mt-5 text-lg text-slate-200/95 max-w-2xl hero-shadow">
      We're picky about which projects we take on and honest about the ones we don't.
    </p>
  </Hero>

  <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-5 py-12 md:py-16">
    <Breadcrumbs items={[
      { href: '/', label: 'Home' },
      { href: '/about', label: 'About' },
    ]} />

    <div class="prose-body">
      <h2>Who we are</h2>
      <p>
        Apriori Studio operates as <strong>Apriori Ltd</strong>, a private limited company
        registered in England and Wales. We're based in London but most of our work is remote —
        clients are spread across the UK, the EU and occasionally further afield.
      </p>
      <p>
        We're small on purpose. The person you talk to about your project is one of the people
        who will build it. That means decisions happen in hours rather than weeks, trade-offs
        get explained in plain English, and there's no chain of account managers between your
        question and the answer.
      </p>

      <h2>What we believe about software</h2>
      <p>
        The name "a priori" comes from philosophy — knowledge derived from first principles
        rather than borrowed from elsewhere. That sounds grand for a software studio, but it's
        roughly how we think about projects. Every brief is different. The right framework, the
        right hosting, the right design pattern for your project depends on your scale, your
        users, your team's existing skills, and what you can afford to maintain. We don't have
        a fixed stack we apply to everyone; we pick what fits.
      </p>
      <p>
        That said, we have strong opinions about a few things that almost always matter:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Boring is good.</strong> We pick well-documented, widely-used tools over the trendy
          option. They're easier to hire for and they'll still be supported in five years.</li>
        <li><strong>Speed is a feature.</strong> Slow sites lose users; slow apps get uninstalled. We
          treat performance as a non-negotiable, not a polish-pass at the end.</li>
        <li><strong>Honest pricing.</strong> Every quote is fixed scope and fixed price. If something
          changes, we put it in writing before doing it.</li>
        <li><strong>You own everything.</strong> Domains, hosting accounts, source code, design files
          — registered in your name from day one. There's no lock-in.</li>
        <li><strong>Maintenance is part of the work.</strong> Going live is the start, not the end.
          We monitor, patch, back up, and answer the phone when something needs attention.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Who we're not for</h2>
      <p>
        We're not the right studio if you need fifty engineers tomorrow, if you want a partner
        who'll say yes to every change without pushing back, or if you're looking for the
        cheapest option in a freelance auction. We charge what the work costs and we're
        upfront about it.
      </p>

      <h2>Get in touch</h2>
      <p>
        The best way to find out if we're a fit is a short conversation. Tell us what you're
        working on, what's holding it up, and what success looks like for you. We'll come back
        with honest thoughts within two business days, and if we think someone else would serve
        you better, we'll tell you that too.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href="/contact">Use the contact form</a> or email
        <Email address={SITE.email.contact} /> directly.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
